               <msContents>
                  <summary>This illustrated copy of the <title>Dābistān-i Maẕāhib</title> (School of
                     Religions) recounts various religious creeds and philosophical systems of Asia,
                     as known to the author, divided into twelve <hi rend="italic"
                        xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">ta‘līm</hi> (teachings) and subdivided into a
                     various number of <hi rend="italic" xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">naẓar</hi>
                     (observations). The author, whose name appears here as <persName
                        key="person_f3013" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Mīr Ẕū al-Fiqār ‘Alī al-Ḥusaynī
                        (ca. 1615–70)</persName>, apparently followed the Āẕar Kayvānī
                     illuminationist sect in India during the reign of the Mughal ruler ‘Ālamgīr I
                     (r. 1658–1707). The author not only travelled throughout the northern
                        <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208" key="place_7000208"
                        >Indian subcontinent</placeName>, but also to Mashhad in Iran. As a result,
                     he became thoroughly acquainted with a great number of religious and scientific
                     Parsi, Hindu, Buddhist, Jewish, Christian, and Muslim personalities and their
                     doctrines. Completed by <persName key="person_f2415" role="scr"
                        xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">Munshī Ghulām Muḥammad bin Muḥammad Jamāl</persName>
                     in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7001592" key="place_7001592"
                        >Surat</placeName> on <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari" when="1801-02-12">28
                        Ramaz̤ān 1215 AH (12 Feb. 1801 CE)</date>, the manuscript contains seven
                     tinted drawings that depict the planets according to Hindu mythology.</summary>
